14.Explain the concept of bus width and its significance in computer architecture:-\par
Ans:- A Bus width refers to the number of bits that can be transmitted simultaneously over a computer bus. A bus is a set of physical connections (cables, circuits, etc.) that can be shared by multiple hardware components to communicate with one another. Memory and input/ output devices are connected to the Central Processing Unit through a group of lines called a bus. These lines are designed to transfer data between different components.\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl276\slmult1\tx284\tx426 Types of Computer Bus\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Address bus \par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Data bus\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Control bus\par

\pard\sl276\slmult1\tx284\tx426\par
\b 1. Address Bus:- \par

\pard 
{\pntext\f0 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent0\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\fi-360\li720\sl276\slmult1\tx284\tx426\b0 A collection of wires used to identify particular location in main memory is called Address Bus. Or in other words, the information used to describe the memory locations travels along the address bus.\par
{\pntext\f0 2.\tab}The address bus transports memory addresses which the processor wants to access in order to read or write data..\par
{\pntext\f0 3.\tab}The address bus is unidirectional.\par

\pard\sl276\slmult1\tx284\tx426\b\par
2. Data Bus:-\b0\par

\pard 
{\pntext\f0 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent0\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\fi-360\li720\sl276\slmult1\tx284\tx426 A collection of wires through which data is transmitted from one part of a computer to another is called Data Bus.\par
{\pntext\f0 2.\tab}Data Bus can be thought of as a highway on which data travels within a computer.\par
{\pntext\f0 3.\tab}The main objective of data bus is transfer of the data between microprocessor to input/ output devices or memory.\par
{\pntext\f0 4.\tab}The data bus transfers instructions coming from or going to the processor.\par
{\pntext\f0 5.\tab}The data bus is bidirectional because the data can flow in either direction from CPU to memory(or input/output device) or from memory to the CPU.\par

\pard\sl276\slmult1\tx284\tx426\par
\b 3. Control Bus:-\b0\par

\pard 
{\pntext\f0 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent0\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\fi-360\li720\sl276\slmult1\tx284\tx426 The connections that carry control information between the CPU and other devices within the computer is called Control Bus.\par
{\pntext\f0 2.\tab}The main objective of control bus is all signals controller carried from processor to other hardware device.\par
{\pntext\f0 3.\tab}The control bus transports orders and synchonisation signal coming from the control unit and travelling to all other hardware components\par
{\pntext\f0 4.\tab}The Control bus is bidirectional because the data can flow in either direction from CPU to memory(or input/output device) or from memory to the CPU.\par
{\pntext\f0 5.\tab}it also transmits response signals from the hardware.\par

